00:11:47.430 --> 00:11:51.130
Mike Auschwitz set up
a program, you know,

00:11:51.130 --> 00:11:53.080
the spirit of the '60s.

00:11:53.080 --> 00:11:57.690
Kennedy I think was
still president,

00:11:57.690 --> 00:12:00.250
to help kids from tough
high school backgrounds

00:12:00.250 --> 00:12:05.350
get into universities,
focus on New York City.

00:12:05.350 --> 00:12:09.070
Over the years, it was a very
successful program, but sort

00:12:09.070 --> 00:12:11.775
of looking at the results a
number of years later in 1980,

00:12:11.775 --> 00:12:13.150
it was determined
that these kids

00:12:13.150 --> 00:12:14.358
were getting into university.

00:12:14.358 --> 00:12:15.940
They were getting
great training.

00:12:15.940 --> 00:12:18.460
But they weren't
getting the jobs.

00:12:18.460 --> 00:12:19.670
They were getting jobs.

00:12:19.670 --> 00:12:20.440
But we all know
there is a difference

00:12:20.440 --> 00:12:22.090
between the jobs and just jobs.

00:12:26.220 --> 00:12:29.344
And so a careers
program was founded,

00:12:29.344 --> 00:12:30.760
and that's what I
participated in.

00:12:30.760 --> 00:12:33.490
That was my ticket when
came out of university

00:12:33.490 --> 00:12:36.794
and ended up at Lehman Brothers,
and that opened my eyes.

00:12:36.794 --> 00:12:39.460
The scales fell, and I could see
the world in a whole new light,

00:12:39.460 --> 00:12:41.626
and it was like, oh, my
gosh, if I do this and that,

00:12:41.626 --> 00:12:43.270
I could accomplish a few things.

00:12:43.270 --> 00:12:45.187
I ended up working at
UBS, then Deutsche Bank

00:12:45.187 --> 00:12:47.270
in a variety of different
functions, transactional

00:12:47.270 --> 00:12:48.800
and strategy jobs.

00:12:48.800 --> 00:12:50.200
And I was here--

00:12:50.200 --> 00:12:52.982
here, I was in London, sorry--

00:12:52.982 --> 00:12:54.190
this morning I was in London.

00:12:57.610 --> 00:13:00.880
Looking out on the trading
floor of the equity sales team

00:13:00.880 --> 00:13:03.460
could have used some
diversity shall we say.

00:13:03.460 --> 00:13:05.610
The corporate finance
equity research departments

00:13:05.610 --> 00:13:07.390
could have used some diversity.

00:13:07.390 --> 00:13:10.090
So I approached the head
of training and development

00:13:10.090 --> 00:13:12.560
said, hey, can we do
this, this SEO thing?

00:13:12.560 --> 00:13:14.920
I mean, it's pretty good.

00:13:14.920 --> 00:13:17.840
I was smiled at, but
ultimately supported.

00:13:17.840 --> 00:13:22.120
I had one awkward
conversation with a fellow

00:13:22.120 --> 00:13:24.230
who ran a recruiting for
a major investment bank.

00:13:24.230 --> 00:13:25.570
He sort of essentially
metaphorically

00:13:25.570 --> 00:13:27.153
patted me on the
head and said, that's

00:13:27.153 --> 00:13:30.020
a really nice American concept
that you're bringing to the UK.

00:13:30.020 --> 00:13:32.680
You know, we don't have a
race problem in this country.

00:13:32.680 --> 00:13:37.910
We have a class
problem, which anyway--

00:13:40.930 --> 00:13:43.420
anyway, so we took off
on the back of a pilot,

00:13:43.420 --> 00:13:44.620
on my credit card.

00:13:44.620 --> 00:13:47.980
We were able to get a
successful pilot program going,

00:13:47.980 --> 00:13:51.100
and then dotbomb occurred.

00:13:51.100 --> 00:13:53.290
I was doing sort
of, at that point,

00:13:53.290 --> 00:13:57.100
sort of fintech 1.0
venture investing

00:13:57.100 --> 00:14:00.100
on the bank's balance sheet
as Pets.com was crashing.

00:14:00.100 --> 00:14:02.000
It was a messy time.

00:14:02.000 --> 00:14:03.850
I ended up going
back to New York,

00:14:03.850 --> 00:14:06.400
and much of the rest of
my involvement over time

00:14:06.400 --> 00:14:08.030
has been on the board.

00:14:08.030 --> 00:14:12.160
I've only recently come back
in the last year to assist.

00:14:12.160 --> 00:14:15.040
