first time in the history

00:23:35.070 --> 00:23:38.280
of-- in the measured
history of race relations

00:23:38.280 --> 00:23:44.190
and social mobility in the
UK, poor, white, working class

00:23:44.190 --> 00:23:47.940
males were the number one
sort of disadvantaged group

00:23:47.940 --> 00:23:49.560
in the UK.

00:23:49.560 --> 00:23:55.500
And we live in an age of, you
know, stay away from politics,

00:23:55.500 --> 00:23:57.780
but when you think about
the rise of a Trump,

00:23:57.780 --> 00:24:03.750
the rise of a Brexit
focus, a lot of folks

00:24:03.750 --> 00:24:06.540
have been left behind in
the UK, who are white,

00:24:06.540 --> 00:24:09.870
working class, and
in a ethnic diversity

00:24:09.870 --> 00:24:14.200
definition of diversity,
are being ignored.

00:24:14.200 --> 00:24:18.750
And so at SEO, we spend
a ton of time on Fariha,

00:24:18.750 --> 00:24:21.120
and we spend a ton of
time on Billy as well,

00:24:21.120 --> 00:24:25.460
because it's just necessary
to reflect in the community.

00:24:25.460 --> 00:24:27.270
Essentially, they
are great people

00:24:27.270 --> 00:24:30.190
with great talent, great
performance, but you know,

00:24:30.190 --> 00:24:32.940
they're up against
different challenges.

00:24:32.940 --> 00:24:37.440
You know, Fariha,
maybe she's Muslim,

00:24:37.440 --> 00:24:43.482
and you know, by virtue
of that is culturally not

00:24:43.482 --> 00:24:44.940
permitted to shake
someone's hand--

00:24:44.940 --> 00:24:47.490
a man's hand, who is not
in her immediate family.

00:24:47.490 --> 00:24:55.830
I mean, maybe she wants
to pray five times a day

00:24:55.830 --> 00:24:59.610
in the middle of a training
program to get into a law firm.

00:24:59.610 --> 00:25:01.650
That's very-- if you're
not expecting it,

00:25:01.650 --> 00:25:03.150
you're not looking
for it, you don't

00:25:03.150 --> 00:25:06.240
know what it is to
observe her doing this,

00:25:06.240 --> 00:25:09.390
that can throw you for a loop.

00:25:09.390 --> 00:25:12.360
Billy may have the wrong accent.

00:25:12.360 --> 00:25:15.300
Billy may have the
wrong references.

00:25:15.300 --> 00:25:17.479
Billy may support the
wrong football team.

00:25:17.479 --> 00:25:19.020
There's a whole
range of other things

00:25:19.020 --> 00:25:22.500
that can get in
the way of a Billy,

00:25:22.500 --> 00:25:23.880
just as they might
with a Fariha.

00:25:23.880 --> 00:25:27.750
They have different challenges,
but conceptually, we're

00:25:27.750 --> 00:25:28.810
talking about difference.

00:25:28.810 --> 00:25:30.101
We're talking about acceptance.

00:25:30.101 --> 00:25:35.310
We're talking about
maximizing the pool of talent

00:25:35.310 --> 00:25:36.570
available to a given firm.

00:25:36.570 --> 00:25:40.200
And in that case, we
see a need for what

00:25:40.200 --> 00:25:44.120
we do all across the map.

00:25:44.120 --> 00:25:49.700
So every firm we work
with is really focused

00:25:49.700 --> 00:25:52.120
on entry-level
graduate recruitment,

00:25:52.120 --> 00:25:54.440
because it's obvious.

00:25:54.440 --> 00:25:57.590
It's like we need, we can find.

00:25:57.590 --> 00:26:03.400
And it's essentially recruitment
in the talent attraction

00:26:03.400 --> 00:26:06.270
and selection business as such.

00:26:06.270 --> 00:26:07.850
It has really
become a commodity.

00:26:07.850 --> 00:26:10.670
There are lots of organizations
out there seeking to do that.

00:26:10.670 --> 00:26:13.880
We had one-- one huge
investment bank come to us

00:26:13.880 --> 00:26:18.254
and say, we don't need
you guys for attraction,

00:26:18.254 --> 00:26:20.420
because we get hundreds of
thousands of applications

00:26:20.420 --> 00:26:22.370
every year from all
sorts of people.

00:26:22.370 --> 00:26:24.650
But no one trains
them like you do.

00:26:24.650 --> 00:26:30.500
And so we see this as the sort
of kind of the easy part of it.

00:26:30.500 --> 00:26:33.860
Getting out to universities,
getting people to apply,

00:26:33.860 --> 00:26:36.590
screening people,
straightforward

00:26:36.590 --> 00:26:38.990
manipulation of a spreadsheet
much of the time--

00:26:41.540 --> 00:26:44.360
a deeper assessment
about personal traits,

00:26:44.360 --> 00:26:46.082
qualifications, and so on.

00:26:46.082 --> 00:26:47.540
And finally, this
is the easy part.

00:26:50.270 --> 00:26:51.830
And one more, please.

00:26:51.830 --> 00:26:55.700
Retention is really
where I see the future

00:26:55.700 --> 00:26:57.080
of all of this working out.

00:26:57.080 --> 00:27:00.406
If you've gone out and
recruited, you know,

00:27:00.406 --> 00:27:02.780
year after year there is this
great, wonderful recruiting

00:27:02.780 --> 00:27:04.821
budget, a whole bunch of
new and different faces,

00:27:04.821 --> 00:27:05.780
that's wonderful.

00:27:05.780 --> 00:27:08.465
But if they're all sort
of veering off one,

00:27:08.465 --> 00:27:12.080
to two, to three years into the
mix, it wastes a lot of money,

00:27:12.080 --> 00:27:14.150
frankly.

00:27:14.150 --> 00:27:16.170
Now, we can talk about
the millennial generation

00:27:16.170 --> 00:27:18.670
and people who want to be in a
place for two or three years,

00:27:18.670 --> 00:27:21.170
and they want to move on, and
that's just the new, you know,

00:27:21.170 --> 00:27:22.940
gig culture inside corporates.

00:27:22.940 --> 00:27:25.970
But fundamentally, I
would like to think

00:27:25.970 --> 00:27:29.900
that a Googler, if they spend
a little more time at Google,

00:27:29.900 --> 00:27:32.780
retain more and more
institutional memory,

00:27:32.780 --> 00:27:35.570
are able to sort of
scale their own networks

00:27:35.570 --> 00:27:37.970
and their own social capital
with benefit to others

00:27:37.970 --> 00:27:38.470
internally.

00:27:38.470 --> 00:27:40.344
If you've got a bunch
of people who have only

00:27:40.344 --> 00:27:41.870
been there for
two years, where's

00:27:41.870 --> 00:27:42.800
the institutional knowledge?

00:27:42.800 --> 00:27:44.216
Where is the
institutional memory?

00:27:44.216 --> 00:27:45.534
Where is the scalability?

00:27:48.440 --> 00:27:50.790
And so a couple of
observations here.

00:27:50.790 --> 00:27:52.640
Maybe we need to
be measuring this.

00:27:52.640 --> 00:27:53.660
How do you measure it?

00:27:53.660 --> 00:27:55.430
Very few people
are measuring it.

00:27:55.430 --> 00:27:58.130
It's like this-- it's like
the next obvious point.

00:27:58.130 --> 00:27:59.660
But I don't know
anyone, frankly,

00:27:59.660 --> 00:28:02.600
any firm that we work with that
is aggressively measuring this,

00:28:02.600 --> 00:28:04.240
because it's sensitive.

00:28:04.240 --> 00:28:07.010
It's politically
fraught with peril,

00:28:07.010 --> 00:28:09.650
if you're going to ask
people to be tracking people.

00:28:09.650 --> 00:28:16.670
In Europe, in some
jurisdictions, it's illegal.

00:28:16.670 --> 00:28:20.000
In France, you know, they prefer
to stick their head in the sand

00:28:20.000 --> 00:28:21.860
and not deal with the
issue, and have it

00:28:21.860 --> 00:28:24.720
bubble up all around them, then
actually deal with it head on.

00:28:24.720 --> 00:28:28.370
And I think a lot of
places are like that.

00:28:31.950 --> 00:28:35.180
So another element of this
is promotion, which is,

00:28:35.180 --> 00:28:36.490
who gets promoted?

00:28:36.490 --> 00:28:38.820
I used that example earlier,
sort of the billion dollar

00:28:38.820 --> 00:28:41.550
pound euro block trade.

00:28:41.550 --> 00:28:44.780
Who's getting the opportunity
to do the cool work?

00:28:44.780 --> 00:28:47.861
I don't know what that
would be in this context.

00:28:47.861 --> 00:28:49.235
But who's getting
the opportunity

00:28:49.235 --> 00:28:51.950
to actually make a difference
such that they can get

00:28:51.950 --> 00:28:52.790
promoted.

00:28:52.790 --> 00:28:53.820
There was a recent--

00:28:53.820 --> 00:28:56.750
I chatted with a guy who's
at a law firm, major, major,

00:28:56.750 --> 00:29:00.380
law firm, who had gone through
a restructuring, a fairly

00:29:00.380 --> 00:29:05.810
dramatic restructuring, and a
lot of people were laid off.

00:29:05.810 --> 00:29:08.217
And this individual, who
is a black man, said to me,

00:29:08.217 --> 00:29:09.800
you know, he didn't
believe that there

00:29:09.800 --> 00:29:14.870
was racism or discrimination
going on as such in the fact

00:29:14.870 --> 00:29:18.169
that seven out of eight sort of
black associates were laid off.

00:29:18.169 --> 00:29:19.960
He said he didn't think
that was the issue.

00:29:19.960 --> 00:29:23.330
He said, they were generally
less qualified, less important

00:29:23.330 --> 00:29:24.500
to the business.

00:29:24.500 --> 00:29:27.530
But the question was,
who was staffing them

00:29:27.530 --> 00:29:30.140
so they actually could
become important to business?

00:29:30.140 --> 00:29:32.840
And that resonates
with me, because I

00:29:32.840 --> 00:29:35.600
think a lot of what
we find around us

00:29:35.600 --> 00:29:38.270
and a lot of the issues that we
see, and we'll get to it in one

00:29:38.270 --> 00:29:44.630
of the last pages, is around
this notion of giving people

00:29:44.630 --> 00:29:48.430
an opportunity to
succeed and promotion,

00:29:48.430 --> 00:29:52.350
build that internal, social,
professional capital.

00:29:56.750 --> 00:29:57.930
Commitment.

00:29:57.930 --> 00:30:02.650
So two simple observations, I
don't know how many of you--

00:30:02.650 --> 00:30:05.891
if there is a lot of turnover
in organizations at large, HR

00:30:05.891 --> 00:30:07.890
departments, especially
the graduate recruitment

00:30:07.890 --> 00:30:10.620
departments, they flip
like nobody's business.

00:30:10.620 --> 00:30:14.080
It's unbelievable how fast--
how many times we have to change

00:30:14.080 --> 00:30:14.580
our--

00:30:17.590 --> 00:30:19.910
we'll come back and
communicate, and recommunicate,

00:30:19.910 --> 00:30:22.680
and overcommunicate what we
do to a new generation of HR

00:30:22.680 --> 00:30:25.260
professionals.

00:30:25.260 --> 00:30:28.624
So people are always moving, and
that's sort of a fact of life.

00:30:28.624 --> 00:30:30.540
But that's not just for
the recruitment folks.

00:30:30.540 --> 00:30:32.206
That's all up and
down the organization.

00:30:32.206 --> 00:30:34.424
So people who you have
support for this premise

00:30:34.424 --> 00:30:36.090
in the organization
will know, and who's

00:30:36.090 --> 00:30:37.270
going to replace them?

00:30:37.270 --> 00:30:40.470
So the firm has to be
committed, and if you

00:30:40.470 --> 00:30:43.260
don't have people in the
executive suite on board,

00:30:43.260 --> 00:30:44.280
forget about it.

00:30:44.280 --> 00:30:46.590
Frankly, it's just
window dressing.

00:30:46.590 --> 00:30:50.400
You need to have people occupied
at the very senior levels.

00:30:50.400 --> 00:30:55.299
I'm really pleased to say
at a place like, you know,

00:30:55.299 --> 00:30:57.340
Aberdeen Asset Management,
obviously has recently

00:30:57.340 --> 00:30:59.850
gone through a merger,
their CEO came and spoke

00:30:59.850 --> 00:31:01.140
to our candidates.

00:31:01.140 --> 00:31:02.630
That's a big deal.

00:31:02.630 --> 00:31:03.434
That's a big deal.

00:31:03.434 --> 00:31:05.100
And one of the
interesting things that's

00:31:05.100 --> 00:31:09.780
occurred over time
is that way back

00:31:09.780 --> 00:31:15.630
in the day, 2000 in my
case, you had a situation

00:31:15.630 --> 00:31:17.250
where diversity was new.

00:31:17.250 --> 00:31:19.000
People didn't know
what to do with it.

00:31:19.000 --> 00:31:20.640
And so it became
in terms of dealing

00:31:20.640 --> 00:31:23.032
with it as a strategic
priority of an organization,

00:31:23.032 --> 00:31:24.990
it went all the way to
the top, because there's

00:31:24.990 --> 00:31:27.900
no one in the middle to sort of
figure out what to do with it.

00:31:27.900 --> 00:31:30.704
And over time, the
bigger firms have really

00:31:30.704 --> 00:31:33.120
embedded diversity into what
they're trying to accomplish.

00:31:33.120 --> 00:31:35.190
But it means that the
eye is off the ball

00:31:35.190 --> 00:31:36.689
in many respects
for many big firms

00:31:36.689 --> 00:31:38.730
from what's happening in
sort of diversity intake

00:31:38.730 --> 00:31:42.660
and management, because it's
been pushed down so many levels

00:31:42.660 --> 00:31:43.350
where we see--

00:31:48.620 --> 00:31:52.470
so what I'm trying to say
is without that support,

00:31:52.470 --> 00:31:53.435
you start to get drift.

00:31:53.435 --> 00:31:55.560
You start to have conversations,
really unfortunate

00:31:55.560 --> 00:31:56.220
conversations.

00:31:56.220 --> 00:31:57.690
I had this one.

00:31:57.690 --> 00:32:02.340
I'm paraphrasing slightly,
but major consulting firm

00:32:02.340 --> 00:32:04.850
who shall not be
named called and said,

00:32:04.850 --> 00:32:10.320
you know, essentially, Andrew,
we need five black people.

00:32:10.320 --> 00:32:12.150
I need them in the
next two months,

00:32:12.150 --> 00:32:15.300
and I'll pay you 2,000 a head.

00:32:15.300 --> 00:32:16.800
That's the conversation
that you get

00:32:16.800 --> 00:32:19.200
when the senior folks
aren't paying attention,

00:32:19.200 --> 00:32:21.870
because it's been devolved
so far down the chain

00:32:21.870 --> 00:32:24.480
it's just somebody who's got
a bums on seats mentality,

00:32:24.480 --> 00:32:27.540
and that's all they're
trying to accomplish.

00:32:27.540 --> 00:32:31.410
So my response was, no, we
can't do that, by the way.

00:32:31.410 --> 00:32:33.460
We could, but we
don't want to do that.

00:32:33.460 --> 00:32:37.750
That's not the discussion that
we want to get engaged in.

00:32:37.750 --> 00:32:44.985
OK, so-- a series of
tiles will pop up,

00:32:44.985 --> 00:32:46.610
and each one sort of
leads to the other

00:32:46.610 --> 00:32:52.460
and sort of tracks the
evolution of what we've seen

00:32:52.460 --> 00:32:56.960
in London in the last 17 years.

00:32:56.960 --> 00:32:59.840
So I'm going to be
nudging you a little bit.

00:32:59.840 --> 00:33:05.630
So does anyone at Google
feel there isn't a diversity

00:33:05.630 --> 00:33:06.530
problem?

00:33:06.530 --> 00:33:09.170
Is sort of acknowledged that--

00:33:09.170 --> 00:33:10.699
AUDIENCE: People exist.

00:33:10.699 --> 00:33:11.990
ANDREW FAIRBAIRN: People exist.

00:33:11.990 --> 00:33:12.662
People exist.

00:33:12.662 --> 00:33:14.870
Well, I think that's-- and
that's hat you tend to see

00:33:14.870 --> 00:33:19.130
as you go forward
through the tiles.

00:33:19.130 --> 00:33:21.260
There's always someone
who is one, or two,

00:33:21.260 --> 00:33:24.320
or three tiles behind, always.

00:33:24.320 --> 00:33:27.560
So we get from
denial to acceptance,

00:33:27.560 --> 00:33:30.400
and then eventually you get a
sense across the industry, what

00:33:30.400 --> 00:33:34.532
we've seen occurs, a lot
of different, underfunded

00:33:34.532 --> 00:33:35.990
groups sort of pop
up saying, we've

00:33:35.990 --> 00:33:37.560
got to do something about this.

00:33:37.560 --> 00:33:40.100
And you know, but
it's my part-time job,

00:33:40.100 --> 00:33:41.630
and I have 10
other things to do,

00:33:41.630 --> 00:33:44.630
and my budget is 1,200 pounds.

00:33:44.630 --> 00:33:46.920
Can you help me?

00:33:46.920 --> 00:33:48.200
So you get this sort of--

00:33:48.200 --> 00:33:52.490
a lot of underweight efforts.

00:33:52.490 --> 00:33:54.500
Through all that,
a handful of firms

00:33:54.500 --> 00:33:56.570
emerge as being really
committed and really

00:33:56.570 --> 00:34:00.230
sort of showing they know
what needs to get done.

00:34:00.230 --> 00:34:02.060
And that's an exciting
moment, because you

00:34:02.060 --> 00:34:05.420
start to see sort of
people taking ahead--

00:34:05.420 --> 00:34:06.850
leading the pack.

00:34:06.850 --> 00:34:12.320
And soon enough,
because HR folks

00:34:12.320 --> 00:34:14.275
have all sorts of
conferences that they go to,

00:34:14.275 --> 00:34:15.650
and they start
talking about what

00:34:15.650 --> 00:34:17.770
they're doing at this firm,
what they're doing at that firm.

00:34:17.770 --> 00:34:19.436
No one admits that
anyone has a problem,

00:34:19.436 --> 00:34:22.639
but there's the cool
things they're doing.

00:34:22.639 --> 00:34:26.060
We see best practices in
air quotes coming along,

00:34:26.060 --> 00:34:27.302
because that's--

00:34:29.870 --> 00:34:33.980
it's the solidification of some
of the early experiments that

00:34:33.980 --> 00:34:36.110
starts to occur.

00:34:36.110 --> 00:34:37.670
Can we go ahead?

00:34:37.670 --> 00:34:40.540
And suddenly, and it's
really-- it's really-- like,

00:34:40.540 --> 00:34:42.570
I'm on LinkedIn, and I've just--

00:34:42.570 --> 00:34:44.138
there's like
diversity awards this,

00:34:44.138 --> 00:34:46.179
and there's diversity
expert this, and everyone's

00:34:46.179 --> 00:34:47.389
a diversity speaker or not.

00:34:47.389 --> 00:34:49.320
And so it's really--

00:34:49.320 --> 00:34:50.350
it's fun to watch.

00:34:50.350 --> 00:34:52.280
I mean, it's everywhere.

00:34:52.280 --> 00:34:55.639
And these are folks who
are now at the cutting

00:34:55.639 --> 00:34:58.850
edge of sort of some of
the early experiments.

00:34:58.850 --> 00:35:01.430
And like I said, there's always
someone who's still back here

00:35:01.430 --> 00:35:02.570
and someone who's
like, yeah, OK,

00:35:02.570 --> 00:35:04.010
but I don't what to do about it.

00:35:04.010 --> 00:35:07.400
Yeah, well, I don't have a
lot of time or money for this.

00:35:07.400 --> 00:35:10.040
But we're certainly at
a point in many places

00:35:10.040 --> 00:35:15.330
today where there's
experts everywhere.

00:35:15.330 --> 00:35:19.220
And so I think
right now, diversity

00:35:19.220 --> 00:35:21.837
has become very
mainstream, and as I said,

00:35:21.837 --> 00:35:23.670
there are people still
at the very beginning

00:35:23.670 --> 00:35:25.490
of the first tile.

00:35:25.490 --> 00:35:29.060
But it's an exciting
time, because there are--

00:35:29.060 --> 00:35:33.660
another firm we worked,
they hired a slate of--

00:35:33.660 --> 00:35:36.470
I think it was six new
entrants into their firm

00:35:36.470 --> 00:35:38.930
for a particular division
in a particular role,

00:35:38.930 --> 00:35:42.080
all white, male from Oxbridge.

00:35:42.080 --> 00:35:44.109
I'm sure they're all
perfectly well talented,

00:35:44.109 --> 00:35:46.400
but one of the leaders on
that team was a senior woman,

00:35:46.400 --> 00:35:50.387
and she was furious
that you know,

00:35:50.387 --> 00:35:52.220
her business, which was
built around working

00:35:52.220 --> 00:35:54.080
with female
entrepreneurs was not

00:35:54.080 --> 00:35:55.820
going to be supported
by-- if that

00:35:55.820 --> 00:35:58.160
was going to be the status
quo, that was not helping her

00:35:58.160 --> 00:35:59.610
in her business.

00:35:59.610 --> 00:36:04.310
So you have people all up
and down sort of a spectrum

00:36:04.310 --> 00:36:05.420
that you see movement.

00:36:05.420 --> 00:36:08.570
And so that firm will then come
to an SEO London or some group

00:36:08.570 --> 00:36:11.420
that might be something like us
and say, how can we help that?

00:36:11.420 --> 00:36:12.770
The next year, by the
way, apparently there

00:36:12.770 --> 00:36:13.920
was six women who were hired.

00:36:13.920 --> 00:36:16.211
So it was yin and yang came
on, and hopefully, now it's

00:36:16.211 --> 00:36:20.031
more three and three, and
fours, and twos at this stage.

00:36:20.031 --> 00:36:20.530
Keep going.

00:36:23.210 --> 00:36:27.620
And so, yeah, some industries
are back here-- certainly

00:36:27.620 --> 00:36:29.690
in a few industries
we see, particularly

00:36:29.690 --> 00:36:34.220
the law firms and
the investment banks,

00:36:34.220 --> 00:36:37.130
it used to be that you'd
blindly go out in April

00:36:37.130 --> 00:36:39.890
and try and recruit for
September of the same year,

00:36:39.890 --> 00:36:41.770
and that was what was done.

00:36:41.770 --> 00:36:45.680
Now, you know, we have a
secondary school program,

00:36:45.680 --> 00:36:48.170
where firms are looking
to draw in pipeline talent

00:36:48.170 --> 00:36:51.410
from that early on to
ensure that they have

00:36:51.410 --> 00:36:54.020
the numbers in gross
form so by the time

00:36:54.020 --> 00:36:56.180
it's whittled down to
their recruiting class,

00:36:56.180 --> 00:36:58.070
that they have the people
they need and want.

00:36:58.070 --> 00:37:00.680
So you know, we've
been living the war

00:37:00.680 --> 00:37:02.931
for talent for a long time.

00:37:02.931 --> 00:37:04.430
You guys, the
Googlers of the world,

00:37:04.430 --> 00:37:08.002
are absolutely putting pressure
on all the big banks, and law

00:37:08.002 --> 00:37:09.710
firms, and consulting
firms, because what

00:37:09.710 --> 00:37:11.251
you do has a certain
je ne sais quoi,

00:37:11.251 --> 00:37:15.140
it's so much more interesting
than prospectuses.

00:37:15.140 --> 00:37:17.870
But you'll tell
me if that's true.

00:37:17.870 --> 00:37:19.620
Maybe they've got it all wrong.

00:37:19.620 --> 00:37:20.820
I don't know.

00:37:20.820 --> 00:37:23.039
If you go to the next--

00:37:23.039 --> 00:37:24.080
I talked about retention.

00:37:24.080 --> 00:37:25.660
I think this is the next front.

00:37:25.660 --> 00:37:28.429
I think people are starting
to wake up to this as they've

00:37:28.429 --> 00:37:28.970
gone through.

00:37:28.970 --> 00:37:30.110
They've done a bunch
of experiments.

00:37:30.110 --> 00:37:31.250
They're trying to figure
out what's going on.

00:37:31.250 --> 00:37:33.050
There are people who
can talk the talk.

00:37:33.050 --> 00:37:35.019
Some people are
walking the walk.

00:37:35.019 --> 00:37:36.560
And now they're
saying, well, sort of

00:37:36.560 --> 00:37:39.860
like what occurred back with
Mike Auschwitz in New York,

00:37:39.860 --> 00:37:42.677
you know, you're getting
kids into university, but not

00:37:42.677 --> 00:37:43.760
necessarily into the jobs.

00:37:46.550 --> 00:37:50.060
We're getting a lot of folks
in, but are they staying?

00:37:50.060 --> 00:37:55.700
And that's the next evolutionary
step, one more step.

00:37:55.700 --> 00:37:57.870
And so, yeah, this is--

00:37:57.870 --> 00:38:01.580
I think of the whole
diversity and inclusion

00:38:01.580 --> 00:38:03.740
agenda as something
that's totally solvable.

00:38:03.740 --> 00:38:06.440
I mean, it just requires will.

00:38:06.440 --> 00:38:09.080
It requires focus,
and the reality

00:38:09.080 --> 00:38:13.040
is that big firms have a lot
of other things to focus on.

00:38:13.040 --> 00:38:18.840
And I genuinely believe
that the people,

00:38:18.840 --> 00:38:21.270
you know, our counterparts
at many of these firms

00:38:21.270 --> 00:38:23.070
sincerely believe
in love and want

00:38:23.070 --> 00:38:25.460
to sort of embrace and advance
the cause of diversity.

00:38:25.460 --> 00:38:27.720
I really believe that.

00:38:27.720 --> 00:38:31.210
There'll be a few exceptions
that you see come and go.

00:38:31.210 --> 00:38:32.915
But I think most
of the people we

00:38:32.915 --> 00:38:35.040
deal with on the other side
of the table sponsoring

00:38:35.040 --> 00:38:37.240
our activities really
believe that they're

00:38:37.240 --> 00:38:38.520
doing what they want to--

00:38:38.520 --> 00:38:39.965
trying to accomplish
these goals.

00:38:39.965 --> 00:38:41.090
But they're under budgeted.

00:38:41.090 --> 00:38:42.690
They're understaffed.

00:38:42.690 --> 00:38:46.170
And so they're forced into
this world where they're

00:38:46.170 --> 00:38:48.630
being shouted out from above
to hit numbers, do this,

00:38:48.630 --> 00:38:51.630
do that, the other, and they're
given a tiny budget to do it.

00:38:51.630 --> 00:38:56.600
And so is the answer just
throw more money at it?

00:38:56.600 --> 00:38:57.290
I don't know.

00:38:57.290 --> 00:38:58.860
I think it's a
cultural question.

00:38:58.860 --> 00:39:00.860
I don't think it
necessarily requires that.

00:39:00.860 --> 00:39:02.574
If you start to figure this--

00:39:02.574 --> 00:39:04.240
the firms start to
figure out retention.

00:39:04.240 --> 00:39:06.950
A lot of the upfront
investment and experiments,

00:39:06.950 --> 00:39:07.970
it solves itself.

00:39:07.970 --> 00:39:10.310
And some firms have
figured it out,

00:39:10.310 --> 00:39:11.780
but most are figuring it out.

00:39:14.350 --> 00:39:20.920
OK, so each one of these topics
could be a book, an HBO mini

00:39:20.920 --> 00:39:23.090
series, you name it.

00:39:23.090 --> 00:39:24.792
But I figured I'd close on this.

00:39:24.792 --> 00:39:27.250
As we go through this, we can
open up and have a little bit

00:39:27.250 --> 00:39:29.764
more dialogue back and forth.

00:39:29.764 --> 00:39:31.180
I think I know the
answer to this,

00:39:31.180 --> 00:39:35.140
but how many people have heard
of the topic unconscious bias?

00:39:35.140 --> 00:39:37.660
Everyone's heard of-- right.

00:39:37.660 --> 00:39:40.775
It's everywhere.

00:39:40.775 --> 00:39:41.900
I don't need to go into it.

00:39:41.900 --> 00:39:44.560
I think the point
is that this is

00:39:44.560 --> 00:39:48.160
on the lips of every
diversity inclusion group.

00:39:48.160 --> 00:39:52.870
This is about as
mainstream as things get.

00:39:52.870 --> 00:39:58.330
But you know, it's not
just I think about the bias

00:39:58.330 --> 00:40:00.610
that we all face.

00:40:00.610 --> 00:40:04.690
Try being a Rohingya Muslim
in Myanmar right about now.

00:40:04.690 --> 00:40:07.646
Try being a South
Korean in Japan.

00:40:10.750 --> 00:40:13.930
In Singapore, a
highly modern society,

00:40:13.930 --> 00:40:18.370
is a lot of tribalism between
Chinese, Malay, and Indian

00:40:18.370 --> 00:40:20.650
populations.

00:40:20.650 --> 00:40:23.620
A lot of those
lines don't cross.

00:40:23.620 --> 00:40:28.270
This is a global issue
I think in the West,

00:40:28.270 --> 00:40:30.430
call it the US and
Western Europe,

00:40:30.430 --> 00:40:33.790
there's a lot of very
positive work going on.

00:40:33.790 --> 00:40:35.951
We should, I think,
as a society,

00:40:35.951 --> 00:40:38.200
sort to be patting ourselves
on the back at some level

00:40:38.200 --> 00:40:39.866
but just knowing
there's a hell of a lot

00:40:39.866 --> 00:40:42.370
more work to be done, the
fact that there's movement

00:40:42.370 --> 00:40:43.730
in the right direction.

00:40:43.730 --> 00:40:49.260
It's really-- you get
racism, or sexism, or ageism,

00:40:49.260 --> 00:40:53.770
and everything is just prejudice
gone wrong in a situation

00:40:53.770 --> 00:40:54.970
where there's uneven power.

00:40:54.970 --> 00:40:55.795
And power flips.

00:41:00.305 --> 00:41:06.780
You know, my father,
who is a white guy,

00:41:06.780 --> 00:41:08.900
was in Jamaica for many years.

00:41:08.900 --> 00:41:12.040
And it was where I was raised
for much of my childhood.

00:41:12.040 --> 00:41:16.720
And you know, a super
well-qualified guy,

00:41:16.720 --> 00:41:20.950
PhD in this and that,
in his specialty,

00:41:20.950 --> 00:41:23.320
experienced a lot of racism.

00:41:23.320 --> 00:41:27.370
It's just he was in a
black dominant country

00:41:27.370 --> 00:41:31.990
with a power base that
was not favoring him.

00:41:31.990 --> 00:41:33.805
So it works both
ways is the reality.

00:41:36.500 --> 00:41:39.010
My mother, who is
black, then, you

00:41:39.010 --> 00:41:42.310
know, from Jamaica coming up
to Boston, experienced sort

00:41:42.310 --> 00:41:43.765
of the flip side, it right?

00:41:43.765 --> 00:41:44.640
So it goes both ways.

00:41:44.640 --> 00:41:46.181
It's really where
is there imbalance.

00:41:46.181 --> 00:41:48.760
So much of our work, whether
we want to call it unconscious

00:41:48.760 --> 00:41:51.460
bias is dealing with power
dynamics, just making sure

00:41:51.460 --> 00:41:53.810
there's as much
evenness as possible.

00:41:53.810 --> 00:41:55.270
And you're never
going to get rid--

00:41:55.270 --> 00:41:57.940
I mean, this whole Harvey
Weinstein thing in Hollywood

00:41:57.940 --> 00:42:00.610
right now is all about power.

00:42:00.610 --> 00:42:03.490
It's that simple.

00:42:03.490 --> 00:42:04.450
It's going to happen.

00:42:04.450 --> 00:42:07.784
It's never going away as long as
there are humans in the world,

00:42:07.784 --> 00:42:09.700
but we can at least start
to address the power

00:42:09.700 --> 00:42:12.080
dynamics and the opportunities.

00:42:12.080 --> 00:42:15.387
So good enough expediency.

00:42:15.387 --> 00:42:16.970
I think a lot of the
challenge we face

00:42:16.970 --> 00:42:17.810
is just because
people are dealing

00:42:17.810 --> 00:42:19.100
with what's good enough.

00:42:19.100 --> 00:42:26.540
The story of C. I just want
to name my dear friend C.

00:42:26.540 --> 00:42:30.740
You know, coming up at
Deutsche Bank years ago,

00:42:30.740 --> 00:42:31.850
our team was growing fast.

00:42:31.850 --> 00:42:33.540
And we needed to hire
someone really fast.

00:42:33.540 --> 00:42:35.120
We needed someone really
good and really qualified,

00:42:35.120 --> 00:42:37.745
so we went to the HR department
and said, we need someone fast,

00:42:37.745 --> 00:42:39.890
and they sent over C.

00:42:39.890 --> 00:42:41.200
And he was awesome.

00:42:41.200 --> 00:42:42.080
He was so good.

00:42:42.080 --> 00:42:45.890
He was like, the best
thing we could have had.

00:42:45.890 --> 00:42:49.580
And then we went back, and the
team kept growing, and we said,

00:42:49.580 --> 00:42:50.630
we need another person.

00:42:50.630 --> 00:42:55.390
We need-- like, C,
who do you know?

00:42:55.390 --> 00:43:00.800
And C went and found G.

00:43:00.800 --> 00:43:04.110
And G came on board,
and he was fantastic.

00:43:04.110 --> 00:43:04.920
He did everything.

00:43:04.920 --> 00:43:06.054
He was a superstar.

00:43:06.054 --> 00:43:07.470
He did everything
we needed to do.

00:43:07.470 --> 00:43:08.400
Life was good.

00:43:08.400 --> 00:43:09.840
We kept growing.

00:43:09.840 --> 00:43:12.600
We went C, G, who'd you know?

00:43:12.600 --> 00:43:15.180
They gave us T. And
then the thing about it

00:43:15.180 --> 00:43:19.020
was, they were all Oxford
blues, sports players, you know,

00:43:19.020 --> 00:43:21.960
white guys who are
super well-trained like.

00:43:21.960 --> 00:43:23.580
They all did an amazing job.

00:43:23.580 --> 00:43:26.220
And so, you know,
this is where I

00:43:26.220 --> 00:43:28.890
think good enough really
drives a lot of things.

00:43:28.890 --> 00:43:32.430
If you can hire the kid out of
Imperial, or Stanford, or MIT,

00:43:32.430 --> 00:43:34.740
or whatever, and
they've this fit

00:43:34.740 --> 00:43:40.770
the mold in a generic, quick
hit sense, why search harder?

00:43:40.770 --> 00:43:44.040
Why expend the extra effort to--

00:43:44.040 --> 00:43:47.080
if what you've got
is good enough.

00:43:47.080 --> 00:43:50.550
I know, aging myself, there
was a Fatboy Slim album

00:43:50.550 --> 00:43:54.840
a bunch of years ago that had
this big sort of lumpy guy

00:43:54.840 --> 00:43:59.130
with a brown T-shirt said, I'm
number one, so why try harder?

00:43:59.130 --> 00:44:05.580
You know, this is sort
of a lot of people--

00:44:05.580 --> 00:44:07.620
you've got what you
need, so why try harder?

00:44:07.620 --> 00:44:10.266
And so I think there's a
really interesting opportunity

00:44:10.266 --> 00:44:11.640
for the firms that
really embrace

00:44:11.640 --> 00:44:13.860
the notion of diversity,
to see the market

00:44:13.860 --> 00:44:15.780
opportunity while you can--

00:44:15.780 --> 00:44:18.540
finance jargon,
arbitrage opportunity,

00:44:18.540 --> 00:44:23.310
to figure out what's
the best way to attract

00:44:23.310 --> 00:44:24.720
more diverse talents.

00:44:24.720 --> 00:44:26.867
You have more qualified
voices in the room.

00:44:26.867 --> 00:44:28.200
So you're actually a step ahead.

00:44:30.970 --> 00:44:35.970
I think this is why I sort
of-- you know, a lot of--

00:44:35.970 --> 00:44:37.650
a lot of firms have
an opportunity,

00:44:37.650 --> 00:44:44.130
a strategic opportunity,
to improve their labor pool

00:44:44.130 --> 00:44:46.950
by just being more open
minded about who fits in

00:44:46.950 --> 00:44:48.490
and just spending
the extra time.

00:44:48.490 --> 00:44:51.611
Could we have found someone
better than C, G, and T?

00:44:51.611 --> 00:44:52.110
Maybe.

00:44:52.110 --> 00:44:53.650
They really good.

00:44:53.650 --> 00:44:56.010
They're really good.

00:44:56.010 --> 00:44:57.900
But I'll tell you,
the team fleshed out,

00:44:57.900 --> 00:45:02.880
we had a Pakistani
guy join the team,

00:45:02.880 --> 00:45:05.250
an Indian guy joined the
team, an Israeli woman

00:45:05.250 --> 00:45:08.550
joined the team, and it was
a much more diverse group

00:45:08.550 --> 00:45:09.870
very quickly on that basis.

00:45:09.870 --> 00:45:11.470
We had a lot of other
things going on.

00:45:11.470 --> 00:45:16.890
But I think a lot of what
we deal with in this space

00:45:16.890 --> 00:45:21.760
is that people say--

00:45:21.760 --> 00:45:24.700
all the firms we work with
were making a lot of money

00:45:24.700 --> 00:45:27.490
before they started
focusing on diversity.

00:45:27.490 --> 00:45:33.430
If you took away all the
storm, and fury, and fun

00:45:33.430 --> 00:45:38.067
of diversity inclusion, most
these firms are making money.

00:45:38.067 --> 00:45:40.150
The firms that actually
choose to go over the hump

00:45:40.150 --> 00:45:43.764
and actually develop that talent
are doing one of two things.

00:45:43.764 --> 00:45:46.180
They're paying lip service to
some issue that's out there,

00:45:46.180 --> 00:45:49.270
or they've generally
said, this is good for us.

00:45:49.270 --> 00:45:50.925
There's a business case here.

00:45:50.925 --> 00:45:52.300
And I think-- I
generally believe

00:45:52.300 --> 00:45:55.360
that there is a very clear
business case for it.

00:45:55.360 --> 00:45:58.870
There are a lot of other things
going on behind the scenes.

