00:46:21.070 --> 00:46:23.716
I found it really interesting.

00:46:23.716 --> 00:46:27.030
My one kicking off
question is you mentioned

00:46:27.030 --> 00:46:29.730
law firms, investment
banking, traditional banking

00:46:29.730 --> 00:46:33.190
are much further ahead than
tech companies and other,

00:46:33.190 --> 00:46:36.134
so what lessons would
you say like a Google

00:46:36.134 --> 00:46:38.860
or other companies that are at
the beginning of the journey

00:46:38.860 --> 00:46:41.657
could take for the for
the more established ones?

00:46:41.657 --> 00:46:43.240
ANDREW FAIRBAIRN:
The number one thing

00:46:43.240 --> 00:46:46.570
I think is run
towards difference.

00:46:46.570 --> 00:46:49.060
If you see something
that's different,

00:46:49.060 --> 00:46:50.830
don't run at it
with a pitchfork.

00:46:50.830 --> 00:46:51.940
Run at it with--

00:46:51.940 --> 00:46:53.860
you know, run towards it.

00:46:53.860 --> 00:46:56.470
Open yourself to it.

00:46:56.470 --> 00:47:04.270
You know, I had an irascible
Turkish cab driver on the way

00:47:04.270 --> 00:47:05.990
out to Heathrow this morning.

00:47:05.990 --> 00:47:07.896
And he was-- he had a
lot of strong opinions

00:47:07.896 --> 00:47:08.770
about a lot of stuff.

00:47:08.770 --> 00:47:09.900
I didn't agree with a lot of it.

00:47:09.900 --> 00:47:11.830
But I was really glad to have
that conversation, because I

00:47:11.830 --> 00:47:13.930
learned a whole bunch
of stuff about Turkey,

00:47:13.930 --> 00:47:16.480
and the situation there, and--

00:47:16.480 --> 00:47:19.280
and he was he was a
little bit out there,

00:47:19.280 --> 00:47:23.080
but I was ready to have
that conversation, because I

00:47:23.080 --> 00:47:24.480
was going to learn something.

00:47:24.480 --> 00:47:28.660
So you know, I
don't know how that

00:47:28.660 --> 00:47:30.834
works in sort of
tech world per se,

00:47:30.834 --> 00:47:32.500
because you have so
many different parts

00:47:32.500 --> 00:47:35.010
of your business.

00:47:35.010 --> 00:47:37.600
But I would say run
towards diversity.

00:47:37.600 --> 00:47:43.100
Run towards difference,
and that's at all levels.

00:47:43.100 --> 00:47:44.300
Internally, you know--

00:47:48.500 --> 00:47:49.400
I think I was--

00:47:49.400 --> 00:47:52.370
I had my eyes open
in particular.

00:47:52.370 --> 00:47:53.330
I live in the space.

00:47:53.330 --> 00:47:54.170
I work in the space.

00:47:54.170 --> 00:47:57.170
I breathe and sleep
this, but I was still

00:47:57.170 --> 00:48:01.910
myself you know, taken aback
the first time I met, you know,

00:48:01.910 --> 00:48:03.470
a transgender person.

00:48:03.470 --> 00:48:06.770
That was just different,
really different for me.

00:48:06.770 --> 00:48:08.999
But how cool is that?

00:48:08.999 --> 00:48:11.540
And I think if you sort of reach
out and sort of bring people

00:48:11.540 --> 00:48:15.560
into the fold, you're
going to learn.

00:48:15.560 --> 00:48:17.360
An institutional will
only learn from that,

00:48:17.360 --> 00:48:20.390
and you're bringing in people
from other sectors that

00:48:20.390 --> 00:48:23.420
are only going to add value.

00:48:23.420 --> 00:48:26.190
It used to be in the
US Midwest years ago,

00:48:26.190 --> 00:48:28.110
it used to be Swedes
versus Norwegians.

00:48:28.110 --> 00:48:28.910
All right?

00:48:28.910 --> 00:48:29.660
I mean this is--

00:48:32.690 --> 00:48:35.330
there's all manner
of talent out there.

00:48:35.330 --> 00:48:38.040
You just need to open
your minds to it.

00:48:38.040 --> 00:48:40.070
And I think Google
is well on the way

00:48:40.070 --> 00:48:41.901
from all the conversations
I have, frankly.

