00:48:49.840 --> 00:48:51.816
So if you started
like in the US,

00:48:51.816 --> 00:48:53.190
and and then you
moved to the UK,

00:48:53.190 --> 00:48:55.690
those two markets are
very much developed

00:48:55.690 --> 00:48:58.770
because of apprenticeships
and graduate schemes.

00:48:58.770 --> 00:48:59.580
So it's kind of--

00:48:59.580 --> 00:49:01.056
I am not going to say it's easy.

00:49:01.056 --> 00:49:02.680
But it's easy compared
to other markets

00:49:02.680 --> 00:49:04.889
to you know, just get the
talent to recruit you know,

00:49:04.889 --> 00:49:06.888
talented young people
from different backgrounds

00:49:06.888 --> 00:49:09.130
and then get them into
the right companies.

00:49:09.130 --> 00:49:11.649
Now, if you are now, you
know, expanding scale

00:49:11.649 --> 00:49:13.190
throughout the
markets, you mentioned

00:49:13.190 --> 00:49:16.960
Bogota, Kabul, I
don't know any others,

00:49:16.960 --> 00:49:18.210
how do you want to start that?

00:49:18.210 --> 00:49:19.960
How do you want to
shape it, because a lot

00:49:19.960 --> 00:49:23.010
of those companies are not
prepared to get young guys

00:49:23.010 --> 00:49:25.440
that, let's say, don't have
all the skills that need to be

00:49:25.440 --> 00:49:27.060
trained in investment training.

00:49:27.060 --> 00:49:29.670
How do you want
to approach this?

00:49:32.349 --> 00:49:33.890
ANDREW FAIRBAIRN:
It's kind of-- it's

00:49:33.890 --> 00:49:36.500
very straightforward in my mind.

00:49:36.500 --> 00:49:38.690
You've defined-- the
victory conditions are

00:49:38.690 --> 00:49:42.320
you need a small set
of sponsors, who are

00:49:42.320 --> 00:49:43.940
willing to buy into the notion.

00:49:43.940 --> 00:49:46.320
You don't need everybody.

00:49:46.320 --> 00:49:49.400
Here it was five firms in 2000.

00:49:49.400 --> 00:49:56.420
Now, it's 60 plus, a small
number of firms that get it

00:49:56.420 --> 00:50:01.910
and a talent pool that you feel
you can access readily enough

00:50:01.910 --> 00:50:06.830
and assemble enough paid
or volunteer support

00:50:06.830 --> 00:50:09.170
to train them enough such
that your training makes

00:50:09.170 --> 00:50:12.240
a difference.

00:50:12.240 --> 00:50:19.260
So much of what is required to
succeed in a corporation has

00:50:19.260 --> 00:50:22.920
to do with showing
up on time, you know,

00:50:22.920 --> 00:50:27.180
dealing with feedback
as it comes, and not--

00:50:27.180 --> 00:50:30.250
things that don't require a
huge amount of intervention.

00:50:30.250 --> 00:50:32.910
And if you're able to
put together a training

00:50:32.910 --> 00:50:35.427
program around
that particularly,

00:50:35.427 --> 00:50:37.260
and you have a few
people who buy into that,

00:50:37.260 --> 00:50:38.760
you've got a program.

00:50:38.760 --> 00:50:41.550
I mean, the question of
sustainability and scale

00:50:41.550 --> 00:50:42.735
comes in.

00:50:42.735 --> 00:50:44.610
That's where you set
your victory conditions.

00:50:44.610 --> 00:50:46.068
Do you want 10
firms or five firms?

00:50:46.068 --> 00:50:49.470
Do you want them
contributing 1,000 euros

00:50:49.470 --> 00:50:53.340
or 25,000 euros each?

00:50:53.340 --> 00:50:55.390
I think just doing
the raw numbers,

00:50:55.390 --> 00:50:57.960
our average sponsorship
across all of our firms

00:50:57.960 --> 00:51:03.120
is just under 20,000 pounds.

00:51:03.120 --> 00:51:08.280
I wouldn't expect that to be the
situation in day one in Kabul,

00:51:08.280 --> 00:51:14.940
but certainly, in our Accra
program in Africa in Ghana,

00:51:14.940 --> 00:51:18.741
that is operating in a much
smaller scale than we operate.

00:51:18.741 --> 00:51:21.240
But they've got 60-something
kids going through that program

00:51:21.240 --> 00:51:22.320
every year.

00:51:22.320 --> 00:51:24.160
It's fantastic.

00:51:24.160 --> 00:51:25.090
It's really fantastic.

00:51:25.090 --> 00:51:30.390
So totally doable in
almost any market,

00:51:30.390 --> 00:51:33.366
but it does have to be
modified to the country.

00:51:37.190 --> 00:51:41.120
AUDIENCE: From one Jamaican
to another, you're welcome.

00:51:41.120 --> 00:51:42.870
I have a question.

00:51:42.870 --> 00:51:47.350
So just in relation to
countries like Jamaica where

00:51:47.350 --> 00:51:50.740
your problem is education
is at the further end

00:51:50.740 --> 00:51:51.580
of the spectrum.

00:51:51.580 --> 00:51:55.490
You're thinking about basic
things like food and survival.

00:51:55.490 --> 00:52:00.260
How do you then get countries
such as Jamaica and others

00:52:00.260 --> 00:52:02.380
to that level
where they can even

00:52:02.380 --> 00:52:05.605
see the importance of
education and moving

00:52:05.605 --> 00:52:07.697
up the ladder in terms of
their career and so on?

00:52:07.697 --> 00:52:10.280
ANDREW FAIRBAIRN: OK, so there's
actually two answers to that.

00:52:10.280 --> 00:52:13.760
One of them has to do with this
question of de-risking at risk.

00:52:13.760 --> 00:52:17.210
This is not--

00:52:17.210 --> 00:52:19.730
Google, it's not
clear to me, is going

00:52:19.730 --> 00:52:21.860
to be institutionally
equipped, and I'm

00:52:21.860 --> 00:52:24.110
happy to be told
otherwise, to take someone

00:52:24.110 --> 00:52:28.582
on who has a long criminal
record with multiple drug

00:52:28.582 --> 00:52:30.290
offenses or this, or
that, and the other.

00:52:30.290 --> 00:52:32.330
Someone is not going
to make it no matter

00:52:32.330 --> 00:52:34.954
how much you intervene, because
the resources to get someone up

00:52:34.954 --> 00:52:37.190
that curve, to get
into that position,

00:52:37.190 --> 00:52:38.390
it's just not effective.

00:52:38.390 --> 00:52:40.430
And we're dealing with
profit-based companies

00:52:40.430 --> 00:52:41.346
at the end of the day.

00:52:44.220 --> 00:52:48.770
So there's sort of an 80-20
rule, and can you get--

00:52:48.770 --> 00:52:52.070
with that 20% of effort, can
you get that 80% of impact.

00:52:52.070 --> 00:52:55.160
And if you're going for people
who are generally struggling

00:52:55.160 --> 00:53:01.250
at the ends of the Earth, that's
just a really hard problem

00:53:01.250 --> 00:53:02.060
to solve.

00:53:02.060 --> 00:53:04.700
And I'll be perfectly honest
and say SEO London doesn't

00:53:04.700 --> 00:53:06.020
have the resources to do that.

00:53:06.020 --> 00:53:09.510
We're not funded to do that.

00:53:09.510 --> 00:53:12.050
That being said, I did try
and start up SEO in Jamaica

00:53:12.050 --> 00:53:14.420
not too long ago,
probably about 2004.

00:53:14.420 --> 00:53:16.840
We managed to get
Queenie, sorry,

00:53:16.840 --> 00:53:20.330
we managed to get Q from a
really rough part of Kingston

00:53:20.330 --> 00:53:25.730
to get a job at UBS in
New York, transforming

00:53:25.730 --> 00:53:27.434
her potential at some point.

00:53:27.434 --> 00:53:28.850
Ultimately, it
wasn't sustainable,

00:53:28.850 --> 00:53:31.010
because the structure of
that-- that program had

00:53:31.010 --> 00:53:34.490
structural issues, overly
reliant on the US visa

00:53:34.490 --> 00:53:36.677
situation, as a first point.

00:53:36.677 --> 00:53:37.760
But we had another effort.

00:53:37.760 --> 00:53:40.240
We tried to make it an
indigenous effort, and we had--

00:53:40.240 --> 00:53:42.429
and I'm forgetting
the gentleman's name.

00:53:42.429 --> 00:53:43.220
He's a billionaire.

00:53:43.220 --> 00:53:45.180
I should remember
billionaire's names.

00:53:45.180 --> 00:53:50.990
But we had a Jamaican born
guy who lives in Canada,

00:53:50.990 --> 00:53:54.830
and he owns a couple of the
banks and a few other things.

00:53:54.830 --> 00:53:57.170
He came down, and
we sat in a room

00:53:57.170 --> 00:54:00.164
with myself, him, and a
few other young Jamaican

00:54:00.164 --> 00:54:01.580
entrepreneurs and
said, how can we

00:54:01.580 --> 00:54:05.660
make this-- use this SEO model
and deploy it in Kingston.

00:54:05.660 --> 00:54:07.850
And this guy said, I'll
give you half the money.

00:54:07.850 --> 00:54:10.555
You guys got to go to the
rest of the world to fund it,

00:54:10.555 --> 00:54:12.680
and I was living in London
at the time, and I was--

00:54:12.680 --> 00:54:14.840
I wasn't going to be
doing this full time.

00:54:14.840 --> 00:54:16.587
He was supplying half the funds.

00:54:16.587 --> 00:54:18.920
I had to look at the rest of
the folks around the table.

00:54:18.920 --> 00:54:19.878
They had to be willing.

00:54:19.878 --> 00:54:23.270
They weren't willing by virtue
of they had other stuff to do.

00:54:23.270 --> 00:54:26.000
It wasn't their
problem in their mind.

00:54:26.000 --> 00:54:31.130
You know, it takes will.

00:54:31.130 --> 00:54:33.662
This is a concept
whose time has come.

00:54:33.662 --> 00:54:35.120
It's not hard to
copy and paste it.

00:54:35.120 --> 00:54:38.180
The barriers to entry in that
sense are low as anything.

00:54:38.180 --> 00:54:39.772
Anybody can set up a program.

00:54:39.772 --> 00:54:41.480
You can even set up
a sustainable program

00:54:41.480 --> 00:54:45.800
if your maintenance
levels are humble enough.

00:54:45.800 --> 00:54:47.634
But it takes will, you know.

00:54:47.634 --> 00:54:50.300
The only way we're able to do it
in London in the first instance

00:54:50.300 --> 00:54:52.480
was I was willing.

00:54:52.480 --> 00:54:53.900
I had a little bit of resource.

00:54:53.900 --> 00:54:56.210
I had some credibility
in my profession,

00:54:56.210 --> 00:54:59.720
and I had a list of about
20 American ex-pats running

00:54:59.720 --> 00:55:03.090
around London who were bored
and looking for something to do

00:55:03.090 --> 00:55:04.751
and were ultimately
were committed

00:55:04.751 --> 00:55:07.250
to what we were doing, and we
were able to that back up that

00:55:07.250 --> 00:55:08.250
effort.

00:55:08.250 --> 00:55:13.190
So to do it in Jamaica, or
Puerto Rico, or wherever,

00:55:13.190 --> 00:55:16.005
it's all doable.

00:55:16.005 --> 00:55:18.111
AUDIENCE: OK, thank you.

00:55:18.111 --> 00:55:18.610
Thank you.

00:55:18.610 --> 00:55:20.318
I've been told this
is the last question,

00:55:20.318 --> 00:55:21.402
so I hope it's a good one.

00:55:21.402 --> 00:55:22.943
ANDREW FAIRBAIRN:
Maybe the best one.

00:55:22.943 --> 00:55:24.460
AUDIENCE: Maybe
the best, exactly.

00:55:24.460 --> 00:55:26.760
Thank you again for
your talk, brilliant.

00:55:26.760 --> 00:55:29.340
You have talked about will
just there, and earlier,

00:55:29.340 --> 00:55:34.740
you talked about how diversity
wasn't a theme back in 2000.

00:55:34.740 --> 00:55:36.430
Maybe [INAUDIBLE]
and there is a lot

00:55:36.430 --> 00:55:38.555
of different teams between them.

00:55:38.555 --> 00:55:40.930
And so it's definitely something
that I've seen a Google.

00:55:40.930 --> 00:55:42.659
Perhaps others
have seen at Google

00:55:42.659 --> 00:55:43.700
in their different roles.

00:55:43.700 --> 00:55:46.004
But how do you get will--

00:55:46.004 --> 00:55:47.420
or how do you
inspire will, or get

00:55:47.420 --> 00:55:50.650
people who are in the middle,
who are not in HR, for example,

00:55:50.650 --> 00:55:53.950
but perhaps actually
high managers, leaders

00:55:53.950 --> 00:55:55.210
within the business?

00:55:55.210 --> 00:55:56.930
They are not C level.

00:55:56.930 --> 00:55:59.716
They are not junior
high up, for example.

00:55:59.716 --> 00:56:02.533
But they have the
potential to be--

00:56:02.533 --> 00:56:03.750
make an impact on diversity.

00:56:03.750 --> 00:56:07.730
But because there are
other priorities, targets,

00:56:07.730 --> 00:56:09.620
business goals, and
so forth, it seems

00:56:09.620 --> 00:56:11.750
like diversity or
inclusion gets pushed out.

00:56:11.750 --> 00:56:14.500
But how do you get will
from the middle teams,

00:56:14.500 --> 00:56:16.500
because from my
perspective, that's

00:56:16.500 --> 00:56:18.280
where you can have
the biggest impact?

00:56:18.280 --> 00:56:22.330
So if they make it, [INAUDIBLE]
it kind of cascades down.

00:56:22.330 --> 00:56:25.395
So I'd be interested to get
you perspective on that.

00:56:25.395 --> 00:56:26.664
ANDREW FAIRBAIRN: Yeah.

00:56:26.664 --> 00:56:28.330
If I can rephrase the
question slightly,

00:56:28.330 --> 00:56:33.220
it's how can folks who are sort
of mid-tier, in mid-career,

00:56:33.220 --> 00:56:35.900
make impact and sort of drive
change in the organization

00:56:35.900 --> 00:56:37.850
by raising attention to it?

00:56:41.490 --> 00:56:42.990
It takes a tiny bit of courage.

00:56:46.580 --> 00:56:49.810
I know so many people who are
in positions of influence that

00:56:49.810 --> 00:56:54.370
are mid-career folks, who have
been able to walk into a room

00:56:54.370 --> 00:56:57.980
and say, why can't
we do more of this?

00:56:57.980 --> 00:56:59.820
Why can't we have--

00:56:59.820 --> 00:57:02.770
if the topic is diversity,
or if the topic is Marmite,

00:57:02.770 --> 00:57:04.060
why can't we do more of this?

00:57:04.060 --> 00:57:07.750
It takes an ounce of political
courage inside the organization

00:57:07.750 --> 00:57:08.800
to say--

00:57:08.800 --> 00:57:11.740
to feel like, you're not going
to get kicked out the room

00:57:11.740 --> 00:57:15.790
and lose your bonus check at
the end of the year for having--

00:57:15.790 --> 00:57:18.662
trying to advance your
own agenda of this sort.

00:57:21.520 --> 00:57:23.336
The firms that get
it right are the ones

00:57:23.336 --> 00:57:25.960
that are open to those kinds of
conversations, where you're not

00:57:25.960 --> 00:57:31.270
penalized for asking for some
sort of change around you.

00:57:31.270 --> 00:57:33.510
But I tell you,
when people do it,

00:57:33.510 --> 00:57:40.090
I know a fellow in
Boston, who he was-- he

00:57:40.090 --> 00:57:41.224
had a role in recruiting.

00:57:41.224 --> 00:57:42.640
He just-- he said,
listen, we need

00:57:42.640 --> 00:57:44.244
to get more diversity
in this firm.

00:57:44.244 --> 00:57:45.410
I'm going to make it happen.

00:57:45.410 --> 00:57:47.260
He just went out
and just created

00:57:47.260 --> 00:57:50.140
a cohort of diversity
in that organization

00:57:50.140 --> 00:57:53.692
just by virtue of his
deliberate action and effort.

00:57:53.692 --> 00:57:55.150
And he didn't get
penalized for it.

00:57:55.150 --> 00:57:56.525
So he kept doing
it, and he said,

00:57:56.525 --> 00:57:59.170
I'm going to keep doing it
until you tell me not to do it.

00:57:59.170 --> 00:58:01.270
And now, there is
a whole, as I said,

00:58:01.270 --> 00:58:04.540
cohort of talent that's
been given access

00:58:04.540 --> 00:58:06.880
to that corporate world,
which are now splintered off

00:58:06.880 --> 00:58:08.660
and gone to into 100 different
things over the years.

00:58:08.660 --> 00:58:09.993
I mean, this is a long time ago.

00:58:09.993 --> 00:58:15.100
But he had to have
the wherewithal

00:58:15.100 --> 00:58:18.290
to just do that in
terms of inspiring it,

00:58:18.290 --> 00:58:20.290
as opposed to putting
your own neck on the line,

00:58:20.290 --> 00:58:25.900
because it's always clever to
have it be someone else's idea.

00:58:25.900 --> 00:58:30.310
There are people all around
who are coming up the hard way,

00:58:30.310 --> 00:58:31.810
many of them are invisible.

00:58:31.810 --> 00:58:35.600
But many of them, if you
just probe just a little bit,

00:58:35.600 --> 00:58:37.600
you'll find that they are
your strongest allies.

00:58:40.990 --> 00:58:42.850
We were at a firm
not too long ago

00:58:42.850 --> 00:58:48.090
and a senior partner in
real estate practice there--

00:58:48.090 --> 00:58:50.290
I mean, real estate is
like tough as nails.

00:58:50.290 --> 00:58:51.730
You guy think tech is hard.

00:58:51.730 --> 00:58:54.550
Real estate, I mean,
that's a brutal business.

00:58:54.550 --> 00:58:59.410
This guy is a partner at a major
law firm running that practice.

00:58:59.410 --> 00:59:01.570
He broke down in
tears when talking

00:59:01.570 --> 00:59:03.240
about how he had come up.

00:59:03.240 --> 00:59:09.425
And what a great ally
to find and tap into.

00:59:09.425 --> 00:59:11.300
If you start to know
the people-- the stories

00:59:11.300 --> 00:59:12.100
of the people around
you, you're going

00:59:12.100 --> 00:59:13.683
to find that not
everyone had it easy.

00:59:17.420 --> 00:59:19.850
And if you can get
their stories out,

00:59:19.850 --> 00:59:22.790
that's a way to have
the empathy and sympathy

00:59:22.790 --> 00:59:24.980
that you need to them when
you bring your business

00:59:24.980 --> 00:59:27.990
case forward and say
why this is a good idea.

00:59:27.990 --> 00:59:30.830
You have support behind you, and
you don't bring just yourself

00:59:30.830 --> 00:59:33.290
and your own neck on the
line, but you bring, you know,

00:59:33.290 --> 00:59:34.998
a little bit more than
that to the table.

00:59:37.370 --> 00:59:42.350
So yeah, I thought
it wasn't too random.

00:59:42.350 --> 00:59:46.020
But I'm grateful for
the opportunity to talk.

00:59:46.020 --> 00:59:47.580
SPEAKER 1: Thanks, Andrew.

